Nicotine Pouch Ban in France

Nicotine Pouch Ban in France: Comprehensive Overview
Background and Legal Status in France

Nicotine pouches are small, tobacco-free sachets containing nicotine (often with added flavorings) that users place between the gum and lip to absorb nicotine
euronews.com
. In France, these products fell into a regulatory grey area for years – they were not classified as tobacco (since they contain no tobacco) and were not approved medications, leaving them outside existing tobacco and vaping laws
anses.fr
. Prior to the recent ban, the sale of nicotine pouches was effectively illegal in France as they were not covered by any specific regulatory framework
bfmtv.com
. However, enforcement was limited, and pouches gained popularity, especially among youth, via online and tobacconist sales in the absence of clear regulations
bfmtv.com
.

 

France has now moved to explicitly outlaw nicotine pouches and similar oral nicotine products. Nicotine is classified as a “substance vénéneuse” (poisonous substance) under French law, meaning its sale or use is tightly controlled
legifrance.gouv.fr
. The Public Health Code allows the government to prohibit any operations involving such substances by decree
legifrance.gouv.fr
. Exercising this power, the French government issued Decree no. 2025-898 of 5 September 2025, which bans the manufacture, distribution, sale, import/export, possession, and use of all oral products containing nicotine (except authorized medicinal products and chewing tobacco)
legifrance.gouv.fr
legifrance.gouv.fr
. This decree, published in the Journal Officiel on 6 September 2025, adds new articles to the Public Health Code to formalize the ban
legifrance.gouv.fr
legifrance.gouv.fr
. It covers nicotine pouches (also called pouches or nicopods), nicotine chewing gums or lozenges, nicotine “balls” or beads, pastes, strips, and any similar oral nicotine delivery forms
modernghana.com
modernghana.com
. Chewing tobacco remains exempt, as do nicotine replacement therapies classified as medications or medical devices
legifrance.gouv.fr
. In effect, France now treats recreational oral nicotine products as illegal dangerous substances, rather than as consumer or tobacco products
modernghana.com
tobaccoinsider.com
.

 

This ban will take full legal effect in early 2026. The decree specifies a six-month vacatio legis: it enters into force on the first day of the seventh month after publication
legifrance.gouv.fr
. Practically, that means the ban becomes enforceable on April 1, 2026
bmjgroup.com
. After that date, nicotine pouches and related products can no longer be manufactured, sold, or even possessed in France without risking legal penalties. Medicinal nicotine gums, lozenges and patches will remain available, but only through pharmacies (some by prescription) as smoking cessation aids
thelocal.fr
thelocal.fr
. The overarching goal, as stated by French officials, is to close the loophole that allowed nicotine pouches to proliferate and to protect public health – especially youth – from a product seen as both highly addictive and insufficiently regulated
