. Until then, France is prepared to go it alone in enforcing a ban within its borders, aligning with a precautionary principle.

Grey Areas, Challenges, and Future Outlook

While the law is clear, a few grey areas and questions remain as France moves toward full enforcement in 2026:

Enforcement on Individuals: Technically, anyone in France with a nicotine pouch in their pocket after April 2026 would be breaking the law. In practice, enforcement may focus on sellers and distributors. It is likely that authorities will not actively seek to charge individual consumers unless there are aggravating circumstances (similar to how possession of small quantities of other banned items might be handled more leniently than trafficking). However, the inclusion of possession/use in the ban gives police and customs a legal basis to confiscate pouches and issue penalties. Travelers entering France with nicotine pouches, for instance, could have them seized. The exact enforcement strategy is yet to be detailed, but France will probably issue guidance to retailers and border agents before April 2026. Learning from Belgium’s first year of enforcement, French inspectors will need to check convenience stores, tobacconists, and even online marketplaces to curb illicit sales
brusselstimes.com
brusselstimes.com
. Significant fines (and for serious offenders, criminal charges) are on the table to deter violation
brusselstimes.com
.

Online Sales and Cross-Border Supply: One challenge is the internet – French consumers might try to buy pouches online from abroad once domestic sales are banned. France can outlaw domestic sales and even try to block websites, but policing online imports is difficult (as seen with other substances). Belgium’s authorities admitted that online sellers remained a hurdle after their ban
brusselstimes.com
. France may need to coordinate with other countries and possibly pressure postal and courier services to intercept nicotine pouch shipments. If a unified EU stance emerges (for example, an EU-wide ban or age-restricted regime), that would simplify matters; but if not, France could see a cat-and-mouse game with websites shipping pouches from jurisdictions where they’re legal.

Industry Pushback and Legal Appeals: As of late 2025, there has been no publicized court challenge to the French ban, but industry could explore legal avenues. One possibility is a challenge under EU law – arguing that France’s ban infringes the free movement of goods or is disproportionate. The European Commission did not outright block France’s decree during the notification process (it allowed the standstill to end), so any challenge might have to proceed in French courts or potentially the European Court of Justice if a company claims EU single market rules are violated. However, because nicotine pouches are not yet explicitly regulated at the EU level, France has some latitude to invoke public health exceptions. Tobacco companies might also lobby the next French government to repeal or soften the ban before it takes effect (especially since the September 2025 decree was enacted right before a government turnover). If political winds change or if the EU adopts a milder regulatory approach in its next Tobacco Products Directive update, France could conceivably amend the law. For now, though, the political consensus (spanning the current government and health agencies) appears strongly in favor of the ban.

Public Awareness and Cessation Support: Another grey area is how current users will be managed. Surveys indicate that in 2022, only about 0.3% of French adults used nicotine pouches, though usage may have grown since
