euronews.com
. Many of these users are likely young and not heavily nicotine-dependent (some may be experimenters). The government will need to communicate the new law to ensure people know pouches are illegal. For those who got hooked on pouches, authorities might encourage them to switch to approved nicotine replacement therapies or vaping if they need to wean off nicotine. France has robust smoking cessation programs (some NRT costs are reimbursed by healthcare), so folding pouch users into these programs could be part of the public health response. Since nicotine gum/lozenges will remain available via pharmacies, dependent pouch users could transition to those under medical advice. The success of the ban in health terms may partly be judged on whether pouch users quit nicotine altogether or substitute other products.

Harmonization with Future EU Policy: In the coming years, the EU is expected to revise its tobacco and related products legislation. France’s action might influence an EU-wide approach – possibly leading to an EU directive that treats nicotine pouches similarly to tobacco (e.g. age limits, health warnings, nicotine caps) or even an EU-wide sales ban if consensus leans that way. France has positioned itself as a leader in strict nicotine control, alongside Belgium. If the EU eventually implements regulations short of a ban, France will face a choice whether to align with the EU minimum or keep its stricter rules (EU law typically sets a floor, but members can maintain stronger measures for public health). For example, if the EU sets a nicotine limit and age-18 restriction for pouches, France could comply by loosening its outright ban – but given France’s stance, it might instead push for an EU-wide prohibition. The outcome will depend on further scientific evidence and the balance of member state views.

Other Novel Nicotine Products: The ban specifically names oral nicotine products, but the nicotine market is ever-evolving. Already, companies have created nicotine products like “tobacco-free snus” (nicotine pouches), nicotine toothpicks, nicotine sachet drinks, etc. France’s definition should catch anything intended for oral ingestion, but one grey area could be nicotine devices (e.g. a future inhaler not classified as a medicine, or nicotine pouches that are labeled as something else). Also, nicotine gels or lotions (absorbed through skin) could appear – though those might be covered under poisons laws similarly. The French government will have to remain vigilant that new nicotine delivery formats don’t exploit loopholes. Given the broad wording of “ingestion or absorption” in the decree
legifrance.gouv.fr
legifrance.gouv.fr
, most conceivable oral or buccal routes are covered. If any product falls outside (like a nicotine lollipop, which is technically food), it might get snared by food safety regulations.

Recent developments (as of late 2025) indicate that France is moving full steam ahead with the ban. The decree is in place, and public health campaigns are likely to precede the enforcement date. France’s stance is being watched by both allies and critics. Anti-tobacco activists internationally have praised France for putting youth health first and not waiting for consensus to act
