.

 

In conclusion, France’s ban on nicotine pouches marks a significant moment in tobacco/nicotine control policy. It underscores France’s philosophy that the safest way to avoid new tobacco-related harm is to preempt nicotine addiction at its source, even if that means banning a product that is arguably less harmful than cigarettes. The coming years will reveal the impact: Will youth nicotine use decline as a result? Will smokers who might have switched to pouches find other ways to quit? Will a black market emerge despite the ban? France is effectively a test case of a prohibition strategy for these products. The government, backed by health experts, is optimistic that in a decade’s time the reward will be a generation far less acquainted with nicotine. As Health Minister Vautrin stated, this measure is about “combatting the risks associated with addiction” and preventing a step backwards in the fight against tobacco
